\par \pard\plain {\listtext\pard\plain \li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-360\f4\f5\fs24\f5\lang1025\qj 15.\tab}\ilvl0 \ltrpar\s1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ls0\li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-360\rtlch\af5\afs24\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af5\langfe255\hich\f4\fs24\lang7177\loch\f4\fs24\lang7177 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f4\fs24\lang7177\i0\b0 It is inconceivable that where the relief sought entails the voiding of a contract that we could grant relief without all the contracting parties being heard. That violates any notion of natural justice or fairness.{\super \chftn{\*\footnote \chftn\pard\plain \ltrpar\s11{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ql\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\loch{\*\cs17\cf0{\*\updnprop5801}\up8\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\loch}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch  }{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f4\fs20\lang7177\i0\b0 See section 52(2) which mandates the Tribunal to conduct its hearings in accordance with the principles of natural justice.}}}
{\*\cs17\cf0{\*\updnprop5801}\up10\rtlch\af6\afs24\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af6\langfe255\hich\f1\fs24\lang7177\loch\f1\fs24\lang7177 } The relief would mean that a party coul
d have its contract set aside as unlawful without it being given the opportunity to be heard to argue the contrary. This approach is not only unfair but also open to abuse. It is especially dangerous when in a case such as this, where the party to the cons
ent order allegedly has a commercial incentive to escape the consequences of its agreement.}
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\rtlch\af5\afs24\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af5\langfe255\hich\f4\fs24\lang7177\loch\f4\fs24\lang7177 
\par \pard\plain {\listtext\pard\plain \li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-360\f4\f5\fs24\f5\lang1025\qj 16.\tab}\ilvl0 \ltrpar\s1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ls0\li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-360\rtlch\af5\afs24\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af5\langfe255\hich\f4\fs24\lang7177\loch\f4\fs24\lang7177 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f4\fs24\lang7177\i0\b0 York and Rance detect in Safcol\'92s willingness to accede to a consent order, a desire to use the Competition Act to rid itself of a commercially troubling contractual regime.{\*\cs17\cf0{\*\updnprop5801}\up10\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\f1\fs24\lang7177\loch\f1\fs24\lang7177  {\super \chftn{\*\footnote \chftn\pard\plain \ltrpar\s11{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ql\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\loch{\*\cs17\cf0{\*\updnprop5801}\up8\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\loch}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch  }{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f4\fs20\lang7177\i0\b0 The papers refer to an ongoing commercial dispute between the parties in relation to inter alia the validity of these clauses.}}}
}}
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\rtlch\af5\afs24\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af5\langfe255\hich\f4\fs24\lang7177\loch\f4\fs24\lang7177 
\par \pard\plain {\listtext\pard\plain \li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-360\f4\f5\fs24\f5\lang1025\qj 17.\tab}\ilvl0 \ltrpar\s1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ls0\li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-360\rtlch\af5\afs24\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af5\langfe255\hich\f4\fs24\lang7177\loch\f4\fs24\lang7177 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f4\fs24\lang7177\i0\b0 We make no comment on whether this cynicism is justifiable, but what it illustrates is the danger of not hearing parties to an agreement who have a clear legal interest in the outcome of the consent order. We find no merit in the Commission\'92s argument that
 we can grant an order in these circumstances without hearing the other parties to the very contractual clauses the consent agreement purports to void. }
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\rtlch\af5\afs24\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af5\langfe255\hich\f4\fs24\lang7177\loch\f4\fs24\lang7177 
\par \pard\plain {\listtext\pard\plain \li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-360\f4\f5\fs24\f5\lang1025\qj 18.\tab}\ilvl0 \ltrpar\s1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ls0\li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-360\rtlch\af5\afs24\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af5\langfe255\hich\f4\fs24\lang7177\loch\f4\fs24\lang7177 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f4\fs24\lang7177\i0\b0 The Commission says that if we do not grant the order in these circumstances it will render the consent order remedy meaningless in future. Counsel for the Commission argued that if a member of a cartel sought to settle with the Commission in circumstances
 where the remaining members did not, the others would be able to object to the consent order claiming a right to be heard. No one would have the incentive to settle, in cases involving multiple respondents unless all of them had agreed to the order.}
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\rtlch\af5\afs24\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af5\langfe255\hich\f4\fs24\lang7177\loch\f4\fs24\lang7177 
\par \pard\plain {\listtext\pard\plain \li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-360\f4\f5\fs24\f5\lang1025\qj 19.\tab}\ilvl0 \ltrpar\s1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ls0\li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-360\rtlch\af5\afs24\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af5\langfe255\hich\f4\fs24\lang7177\loch\f4\fs24\lang7177 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f4\fs24\lang7177\i0\b0 This is not so. The problem in this case is not the need to gain the consent of all respondents, but the nature of the remedy. This is not a case where Safcol is pleading guilty and agreeing to a fine. It is agreeing to the Tribunal ordering the excision o
f clauses from its contracts without us hearing from the other parties to those contracts. It is surprising that such an inappropriate use of the consent order procedure was not obvious to the Commission. In the case of a cartel member admitting to a contr
avention of section 4 of the Act and agreeing to pay a fine the consent of the other members of the alleged cartel would not be required if the remedy does not seek to vitiate the cartel agreement. The remaining members of the alleged cartel would thus be 
free in any subsequent proceeding to assert the lawfulness of their agreement as the prior consent order had not invalidated it. }
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\rtlch\af5\afs24\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af5\langfe255\hich\f4\fs24\lang7177\loch\f4\fs24\lang7177 
\par \pard\plain {\listtext\pard\plain \li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-360\f4\f5\fs24\f5\lang1025\qj 20.\tab}\ilvl0 \ltrpar\s1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ls0\li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-360\rtlch\af5\afs24\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af5\langfe255\hich\f4\fs24\lang7177\loch\f4\fs24\lang7177 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f4\fs24\lang7177\i0\b0 We now turn to the other leg of the argument, which was advanced by Safcol, and it appears by the Commission in the alternative. That is that we must hear York and Rance but after hearing them the order can still be granted if they have not satisfied us th
at the agreements do not constitute prohibited practices. Both York and Rance point out that this is an absurdity. Consent order proceedings are by definition not intended to be contested proceedings. For that the normal complaint referral proceedings appl
y. }
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\rtlch\af5\afs24\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af5\langfe255\hich\f4\fs24\lang7177\loch\f4\fs24\lang7177 
\par \pard\plain {\listtext\pard\plain \li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-360\f4\f5\fs24\f5\lang1025\qj 21.\tab}\ilvl0 \ltrpar\s1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ls0\li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-360\rtlch\af5\afs24\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af5\langfe255\hich\f4\fs24\lang7177\loch\f4\fs24\lang7177 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f4\fs24\lang7177\i0\b0 The briefest examination of the consent order regime illustrates that that cannot be so. In the first place a consent order can be granted even before there has even been a complaint referral. (See Rule 18 of the Rules of the Competition Commission). It is
 noteworthy that in this case the complaint referral was founded on a case in terms of section 9 of the Act, which deals with price discrimination by a dominant firm. The consent order however is premised on section 5 of the Act, which deals with vertical 
restrictive practices. Thus York and Rance would have to meet a case in terms of section 5(1) without the benefit of a complaint referral making out a case in terms of this section of the Act.}
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\rtlch\af5\afs24\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af5\langfe255\hich\f4\fs24\lang7177\loch\f4\fs24\lang7177 
\par \pard\plain {\listtext\pard\plain \li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-360\f4\f5\fs24\f5\lang1025\qj 22.\tab}\ilvl0 \ltrpar\s1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ls0\li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-360\rtlch\af5\afs24\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af5\langfe255\hich\f4\fs24\lang7177\loch\f4\fs24\lang7177 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f4\fs24\lang7177\i0\b0 Secondly section 49D of the Act provides that the Tribunal may grant a consent order without hearing any evidence. This suggests that the legislature never contemplated that the consent proceeding could itself become a contested proceeding on the merits. T
he legislative intent appears quite the contrary.}
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\rtlch\af5\afs24\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af5\langfe255\hich\f4\fs24\lang7177\loch\f4\fs24\lang7177 
\par \pard\plain {\listtext\pard\plain \li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-360\f4\f5\fs24\f5\lang1025\qj 23.\tab}\ilvl0 \ltrpar\s1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ls0\li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-360\rtlch\af5\afs24\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af5\langfe255\hich\f4\fs24\lang7177\loch\f4\fs24\lang7177 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f4\fs24\lang7177\i0\b0 Thirdly, the Act makes it clear that a consent order is not appealable.{\super \chftn{\*\footnote \chftn\pard\plain \ltrpar\s11\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\loch{\*\cs17\cf0{\*\updnprop5801}\up8\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\loch}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch  }{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f4\fs20\lang7177\i0\b0 Section 37(1)(b)(i) which states that The Competition Appeal Court may review any decision of the Competition Tribunal; or consider an appeal arising from the Competition Tribunal in respect of {\cf1 any of its final decisions, other than a consent order.}}}}
{\*\cs17\cf0{\*\updnprop5801}\up10\rtlch\af6\afs24\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af6\langfe255\hich\f1\fs24\lang7177\loch\f1\fs24\lang7177 } As counsel for Rance argued, it would be inconceivable that a contested proceeding could be decided upon without the parties having a right of appeal.}
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\rtlch\af5\afs24\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af5\langfe255\hich\f4\fs24\lang7177\loch\f4\fs24\lang7177 
